<section xml:id="sec_exponential_and_logarithmic_functions">
  <title>Exponential and Logarithmic Functions</title>
  <p>
        <idx><h>mathematical functions</h><h>exponential</h></idx>
        <idx><h>mathematical functions</h><h>logarithmic</h></idx>
  </p>
  <p>
    Another common command that we will frequently use is <c>exp()</c>.
    This is meant to be used as the exponential function.
    Unfortunately,
    simply typing in <m>{ e}^x</m> using the <sq>e</sq> key on the keyboard will not perform the correct operation.
    Instead, Maple treats <sq>e</sq> as it does any other letter,
    such as <sq>x</sq> or <sq>y</sq>.
  </p>
  <aside>
    <p>
      The <c>exp()</c> command can also be found in the Expression palette by clicking the <m>{ e}^a</m> button.
      Similarly, you can get the numerical value <m>{ e}</m> by clicking on its button in the Common Symbols palette.
    </p>
  </aside>
  <p>
    \begin{maplegroup} \begin{mapleinput} {exp(a); } \end{mapleinput} \relax \begin{maplelatex} {exp(a)}{
    <me>
      \displaystyle {{ e}^{a}}
    </me>
  </p>
  <p>
    } <idx><h>mathematical functions</h><h>exponential function</h></idx> \end{maplelatex} \end{maplegroup}
  </p>
  <p>
    We will mostly be using the natural logarithm in calculus,
    but Maple provides commands for logarithms with different bases:
  </p>
  <p>
    \begin{mapleinput} {ln( );} <idx><h>mathematical functions</h><h>logarithmic@natural logarithmic</h></idx> \end{mapleinput} \begin{mapleinput} {log( );} <idx><h>mathematical functions</h><h>logarithmic</h></idx> \end{mapleinput} \begin{mapleinput} {log10( );} <idx><h>mathematical functions</h><h>logarithmic</h></idx> \end{mapleinput}
  </p>
</section>